DOI: 10.1016/j.atherosclerosis.2014.05.953
PMID: 24953487 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


552. Indian Pediatr. 2014 May;51(5):385-7. doi: 10.1007/s13312-014-0414-z.

Health-related quality of life in children with cerebral palsy and their 
families.

Dobhal M(1), Juneja M, Jain R, Sairam S, Thiagarajan D.

Author information:
(1)Santosh College of Physiotherapy, Santosh Medical College and Hospital, 
Ghaziabad, UP; and Child Development Center, Maulana Azad Medical College, New 
Delhi; India. Correspondence to: Prof Monica Juneja, C-77, South Extension -II, 
New Delhi 110 049, India. drmonicajuneja@gmail.com.

OBJECTIVE: To determine the health-related quality of life in children with 
cerebral palsy and their families.
METHODS: One hundred children (3-10 years of age) receiving regular 
rehabilitation therapy for cerebral palsy for last 1 year at a Child Development 
Centrer were enrolled and the Lifestyle assessment questionnaire - cerebral 
palsy was administered to the parents.
RESULTS: 9% had good, 24% had mildly-affected, 37% had moderately-affected and 
30% had severely-affected health-related quality of life. The physical 
independence, mobility and social integration dimensions were much more severely 
affected than the clinical burden, economic burden and schooling dimensions.
CONCLUSION: Health-related quality of child is affected in most children with 
cerebral palsy.

